    <para id="id115569">An arbitrary class <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mo>{</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mi>t</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo>:</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.277778em"/><m:mi>t</m:mi><m:mo>∈</m:mo><m:mi>T</m:mi><m:mo>}</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> of random vectors is conditionally independent, give <emphasis effect="italics">Z</emphasis>,
iff such a product rule holds for each finite subclass or two or more members of the class.</para>
    <!--empty paragraphs get left behind.-->
    <para id="id115617"><emphasis effect="italics">Remark</emphasis>. The expression “for all Borel sets <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>M</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.277778em"/><m:mi>N</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math>,” here and elsewhere, implies the sets are
on the appropriate codomains. Also, the expressions below “for all Borel functions <emphasis effect="italics">g</emphasis>,” etc.,
imply that the functions are real-valued, such that the indicated expectations are finite.</para>
    <!--empty paragraphs get left behind.-->
